WHAT IS THIS KINGDOM
The domain that defines the compression, transport, quality
assessment, and synchronization standards that govern video from
acquisition to distribution. It contains the core tools of modern
codecs (H.266/VVC, AV1, AV2), video quality metrics (PSNR, SSIM,
VMAF), SMPTE timecode and synchronization protocols, IP-based
transport (ST 2110), and the rate-distortion optimization
frameworks that balance bandwidth and quality. It is the layer
that ensures a video signal remains mathematically intact and
temporally coherent from camera to screen.

WHY IT EXISTS
A perfectly graded image is worthless if compression destroys
its color fidelity or if a frame drops in broadcast. This kingdom
provides the engineering standards that preserve the visual
integrity established by all preceding Kingdoms. It replaces
empirical compression tuning with mathematically defined
rate-distortion optimization, defines the timecode and sync
protocols that keep multi-camera arrays in lockstep, and
establishes objective quality metrics that correlate with
human perception.

HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Seven sub-domains: Codec Compression Tools (VVC and AV1/AV2),
Rate-Distortion Optimization, Video Quality Metrics (PSNR, SSIM,
VMAF), SMPTE Timecode and Synchronization, IP Transport (ST 2110),
High Dynamic Range in Broadcast, and Codec-Aware Color Management.
Each section provides the normative formulas, their derivation,
and their GIOP implementation requirements.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
Broadcast encoding (ATSC 3.0, DVB-T2), OTT streaming (Netflix,
YouTube), IMF mastering and packaging, live production (12G-SDI,
ST 2110), archival preservation, and quality control automation.

WHO USES IT
Broadcast engineers, encoding specialists, QC technicians,
streaming service architects, and anyone responsible for
delivering video content without loss of visual quality.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Eliminates codec-induced color shifts by mandating codec-aware
color management. Prevents frame drops and lip-sync errors in
broadcast via rigorous timecode and PTP sync. Replaces subjective
quality assessment with perceptually validated objective metrics,
enabling automated, reproducible quality control at scale.

1. CODEC COMPRESSION TOOLS (VVC, AV1, AV2)
Modern codecs achieve compression through a combination of
prediction, transform, quantization, and entropy coding.

H.266/VVC (Versatile Video Coding):
  Block structure: quadtree plus multi-type tree (QT+MTT) enables
  flexible block partitioning down to 4x4 luma samples.
  Intra prediction: 67 directional modes plus wide-angle extensions.
  Inter prediction: affine motion compensation, bi-directional
  optical flow (BDOF), decoder-side motion vector refinement (DMVR).

  Cross-Component Linear Model (CCLM): predicts chroma samples from
  reconstructed luma samples using a linear model:
    pred_C[i,j] = a * L'[i,j] + b
  where (a,b) are derived by linear regression from neighboring
  reconstructed samples:
    a = (N * sum(L'*C) - sum(L') * sum(C)) / (N * sum(L'^2) - (sum(L'))^2)
    b = (sum(C) - a * sum(L')) / N
  CCLM reduces chroma residual energy by approximately 40% compared
  to HEVC, with no side information beyond the mode flag.

  Transform: Multiple Transform Selection (MTS) with DCT-II, DST-VII,
  and DCT-VIII. Low-Frequency Non-Separable Transform (LFNST) for
  secondary transform on low-frequency coefficients.

  Loop filters: Deblocking filter, Sample Adaptive Offset (SAO),
  Adaptive Loop Filter (ALF). The neural loop filter (VVC-AI, 2025)
  adds a CNN-based filter conditioned on QP.

AV1 (AOMedia Video 1):
  Block partitioning: 10-way partition tree, up to 128x128 superblocks.
  Intra prediction: directional, smooth, recursive filtering modes.
  Inter prediction: compound prediction (two references averaged),
  warped motion (affine), overlapped block motion compensation (OBMC).
  Transform: DCT, ADST, flipADST, identity.
  Loop filters: deblocking, Constrained Directional Enhancement
  Filter (CDEF), Loop Restoration (Wiener and self-guided).

AV2 (AOMedia Video 2, expected final 2026):
  Extends AV1 with improved rate-distortion optimization (Lagrangian
  with perceptual lambda), neural post-filter, and enhanced film
  grain synthesis. Targets 40% bitrate reduction over AV1 at
  equivalent VMAF.

2. RATE-DISTORTION OPTIMIZATION (RDO)
Encoding decisions are governed by minimizing a Lagrangian cost:
  J = D + lambda * R
where D is distortion (e.g., Sum of Squared Errors, SSE), R is
rate in bits, and lambda is the Lagrange multiplier.

Lambda derivation in VVC and AV1:
  lambda = lambda_base * Q_scale[QP][temporal_layer]
For SDR content, lambda_base is proportional to QP^2.
For HDR content, an additional luminance-weighted distortion term
biases lambda to preserve shadow detail. Perceptual RDO uses
SSIM or VMAF-inspired weighting in the distortion term D.

GIOP specification: any GIOP-certified encoder must report the
lambda values and perceptual weighting curves used, enabling
decoder-side fidelity verification against the original scene-
referred master.

3. VIDEO QUALITY METRICS (PSNR, SSIM, VMAF)
Objective metrics enable automated quality control. GIOP mandates
a suite of three complementary metrics.

PSNR (Peak Signal-to-Noise Ratio):
  MSE = (1/MN) * sum_x sum_y (I(x,y) - I'(x,y))^2
  PSNR = 10 * log10((2^bitdepth - 1)^2 / MSE)
Limitations: purely pixel-based, does not model perception.

SSIM (Structural Similarity Index):
  SSIM(x,y) = ((2*mu_x*mu_y + C1)*(2*sigma_xy + C2)) /
              ((mu_x^2 + mu_y^2 + C1)*(sigma_x^2 + sigma_y^2 + C2))
Combines luminance, contrast, and structure. Better correlation
with subjective quality than PSNR.

VMAF (Video Multimethod Assessment Fusion, Netflix):
  Three elementary metrics per frame:
    VIF: Visual Information Fidelity (4-level steerable pyramid).
    ADM: Additive Detail Metric (DWT domain).
    Motion: temporal difference magnitude, normalized.
  Feature vector F = [VIF, ADM, Motion] is fused via a pre-trained
  SVM:
    VMAF = sum_i w_i * K(F, support_vector_i) + b
  Trained on the Netflix public dataset (>10,000 clips, >100,000
  human ratings). Pearson correlation with subjective MOS is
  approximately 0.98.

GIOP requires VMAF as the primary metric for any codec evaluation.
The VMAF model version, training dataset, and viewing conditions
(display, distance) must be recorded in the QC report.

4. SMPTE TIMECODE AND SYNCHRONIZATION
SMPTE ST 12-1 defines timecode formats for frame-accurate editing.

Drop-Frame Timecode (30/1.001 fps = 29.97002997 Hz):
  Frames are counted from 00:00:00;00.
  Rule: drop two frame numbers every minute except minutes divisible
  by 10.
  dropped_frames = 2 * (minutes - floor(minutes/10))
  N_drop_frame = N_total - dropped_frames
  Time in seconds: T = N_drop_frame / 29.97002997

Non-drop-frame timecode: all frame numbers are counted sequentially.
Time in seconds = N_total / fps.

Genlock and PTP (IEEE 1588 Precision Time Protocol):
  SMPTE ST 2059 defines PTP profiles for broadcast. Sub-microsecond
  accuracy is achievable on managed Ethernet networks. PTP locks
  the sample clock, frame sync, and timecode across all devices in
  a facility.

GIOP requires timecode to be embedded as ACESclip metadata for
every frame, along with the PTP grandmaster ID and the frame's
capture or rendering timestamp in TAI (International Atomic Time).

5. IP TRANSPORT (SMPTE ST 2110)
SMPTE ST 2110 separates video, audio, and ancillary data into
separate IP streams.

ST 2110-10: System timing and definitions. PTP for synchronization.
ST 2110-20: Uncompressed video transport. RTP payload format for
  video essence, up to 8K 120p. 10-bit and 12-bit 4:2:2 color
  sampling is typical. Colorimetry signaled via SDP parameters
  referencing ITU-R BT.2100 or ST 2084.
ST 2110-21: Traffic shaping and delivery timing. Defines narrow
  (N), wide-synchronous (W), and asynchronous (A) senders.
ST 2110-30: PCM digital audio transport.
ST 2110-40: Ancillary data transport (timecode, captions, metadata).

GIOP's interlock with ST 2110: the SDP (Session Description Protocol)
must include a GIOP color space identifier, the IDT used, the LMT
stack, and the ODT target. This enables automated color pipeline
configuration in receiving devices.

6. HIGH DYNAMIC RANGE IN BROADCAST
Broadcast HDR is standardized in ITU-R BT.2100.

Formats:
  PQ (ST 2084): absolute luminance, 0 to 10 000 cd/m^2.
  HLG (Hybrid Log-Gamma): relative luminance, backward compatible
    with SDR displays.

BT.2111 specifies HDR color bar test patterns for signal chain
alignment.

BT.2408 provides operational practices for HDR television production,
including down-mapping to SDR and the concept of "reference white"
(203 cd/m^2 for PQ, 75% HLG signal).

GIOP encodes all broadcast deliverables with a metadata track
specifying the HDR format, mastering display peak luminance
(in cd/m^2), MaxFALL (Maximum Frame Average Light Level), and
MaxCLL (Maximum Content Light Level), following SMPTE ST 2086.

7. CODEC-AWARE COLOR MANAGEMENT
Codecs can introduce color shifts if the internal encoding color
space does not match the grading or display color space.

GIOP codec-aware color management mandates:
  a. The encoder operates in a perceptually uniform encoding
     (ICtCp for HDR, or a GIOP-defined log space for SDR),
     minimizing visible quantization artifacts per bit.
  b. The encoder's internal color transform is signaled in the
     bitstream or container metadata, enabling the decoder to
     invert it exactly and reconstruct the original scene-referred
     or display-referred signal.
  c. Chroma subsampling (4:2:0, 4:2:2) filters must use GIOP-
     defined anti-aliasing kernels that preserve color fidelity
     at subpixel edges, with the kernel coefficients recorded
     in metadata.
  d. A GIOP-certified decoder must output linear ACES2065-1 or
     the specified display-referred color space, with certification
     verified by comparing decoded output to the original master
     using VMAF and CIEDE2000 on a standard test suite.

